    <id>https://community.sap.com/t5/technology-blogs-by-sap/exchange-jwt-token-from-azure-with-token-issued-by-sap-cloud-identity/bc-p/13631821#M170728</id>
    <title>Re: Exchange JWT token from Azure with token issued by SAP Cloud Identity Authentication Service</title>
    <updated>2024-03-07T23:09:57.648000+01:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>gregorw</name>
      <uri>https://community.sap.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/12545</uri>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;P&gt;Hello,&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;thank you for this great overview post about the OAuth Token Exchange. But I have some questions regarding the step where you&amp;nbsp;create an xsuaa instance with plan&amp;nbsp;&lt;STRONG&gt;apiaccess&lt;/STRONG&gt;&amp;nbsp;and the corresponding service key to be used for exchanging the IAS token to a XSUAA token:&lt;/P&gt;&lt;OL&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Why do you use the apiaccess plan? With the created service key you could also get directly a token that can be used to create and update users in the subaccount. I think this is not intended. You better would create a xsuaa instance with plan application or?&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;Why do you do another token exchange instead of configuring the endpoint like the &lt;A href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@sap/approuter#authentication-with-identity-service-ias" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow noreferrer"&gt;approuter&lt;/A&gt; or the &lt;A href="https://cap.cloud.sap/docs/node.js/authentication#ias" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow noreferrer"&gt;CAP&lt;/A&gt; application to directly support the IAS token? This would avoid another request response cycle.&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;/OL&gt;&lt;P&gt;Looking forward to your answer.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Best Regards&lt;BR /&gt;Gregor&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
    <link href="https://community.sap.com/t5/technology-blogs-by-sap/exchange-jwt-token-from-azure-with-token-issued-by-sap-cloud-identity/bc-p/13631821#M170728"/>
    <published>2024-03-07T23:09:57.648000+01:00</published>
  </entry>
